\title{Functional Data Depth Features}
\description{
Computes the data depth of functional features via \code{\link[tf:tf_depth]{tf::tf_depth()}}.
Data depth measures how central each curve is relative to the others: values close to \code{1} indicate central curves
and values close to \code{0} indicate extreme curves.

The depth is computed in-sample, i.e. each curve is scored relative to the other curves in the same data. The same
operation is applied during training and prediction.

Irregular curves are interpolated to a common grid before the depth is computed. Curves that remain incomplete
after interpolation (e.g. because they only cover part of the grid) are assigned a depth of \code{NA}.
}
\details{
The \code{"MHI"} method ranks functions from lowest (\code{0}) to highest (\code{1}) instead of from most extreme to most central.
The \code{"RPD"} method relies on random projections, so set a seed (e.g. via \code{\link[=set.seed]{set.seed()}}) before training for
reproducible results.
}
\section{Parameters}{

The parameters are the parameters inherited from \code{\link[mlr3pipelines:PipeOpTaskPreprocSimple]{PipeOpTaskPreprocSimple}},
as well as the following parameters:
\itemize{
\item \code{method} :: \code{character(1)}\cr
The depth method to use. One of \code{"MBD"} (modified band depth, the default), \code{"MHI"} (modified hypograph index),
\code{"FM"} (Fraiman-Muniz), \code{"FSD"} (functional spatial depth), or \code{"RPD"} (regularized projection depth).
Initial value is \code{"MBD"}.
\item \code{na.rm} :: \code{logical(1)}\cr
Whether to remove missing observations before computing the depth. Initial value is \code{TRUE}.
\item \code{u} :: \code{numeric(1)}\cr
Quantile level for the regularization. Only used when \code{method} is \code{"RPD"}. Default is \code{0.01}.
\item \code{n_projections} :: \code{integer(1)}\cr
